        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/33435",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "1111 is recognised as 1.1.11 -> 01. Jan.2011 and therefor true",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-08-13T09:30:38.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-08-13T09:30:38.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/33443",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rufinus",
                        "name": "rufinus",
                        "displayName": "Ludwig Ruderstaller",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thomas, for what can i specify a format if it doesnt matter. \nSorry for me this makes no sense. \nMaybe its ok for isDate alone, but Zend_Form_Validator_Date uses isDate for validation, and in this case this is pointless.\n\nbtw. 111 is true too, what would this be ? 01.01.0001 | 1901 | 2001 ? :-)\n\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rufinus",
                        "name": "rufinus",
                        "displayName": "Ludwig Ruderstaller",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-08-13T13:11:45.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-08-13T13:11:45.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/33444",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I did not say that this behaviour is correct nor did I close the issue.\nActually seperators are not detected.\n\nRegarding 111, this depends on the used format.\n\nddMMYY will recognise it as 01.Jan.2001\nddMMYYYY will recognise it as 01.Jan0001",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-08-13T13:25:27.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-08-13T13:25:27.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/33445",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rufinus",
                        "name": "rufinus",
                        "displayName": "Ludwig Ruderstaller",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "sorry if my wording came out a bit rude :)\n\njust to be sure i understand it correctly:\n\nshouldnt a format of ddMM imply a string length of 4 ?\n\neg.\nddMM == 0108 (01.08. )\nddMM != 108 (1.08)\n\ncouse  if not  112   could mean 1.12 or 11.2\n\nthe convertPhpToIsoFormat is used, which \"normalize\" the format string\nddMM stays untouched but dM would be transformed to ddMMM\nand know it comes jM would be dMMM\n\nthe example with 112:\ndM == ddMMM 11.2\nddM == ddMMM  11.2\njM == dMMM  1.12\n\nso as i see it, the code takes the format right. if dd the day \"must\" have a strlen of 2, if j the day \"must\" have a strlen of 1\n\nbut maybe i missunderstand the whole class , would be probably better I go to bed :)\n\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=rufinus",
                        "name": "rufinus",
                        "displayName": "Ludwig Ruderstaller",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-08-13T13:56:15.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-08-13T13:56:15.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/33447",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "No, MM could also be the localized month representation (f.e. Jan).\nThe convertPhpToIso method is not called except you explicitly set the GNU format manually which you did not according to the given format examples.\n\nd does not mean strlen 1, as it is not the date as string but it's the format.\nd as defined by ISO means a day representation with MINIMUM one digit.\nThis means \"1\" is acceptable as also \"01\" or \"10\n\nBut this has no information for the issue nor does it add any benefit for it.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-08-13T14:26:37.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-08-13T14:26:37.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/35100",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=sg",
                        "name": "sg",
                        "displayName": "Steven George",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I can't see what use the isDate function has.  Thomas Weidner said on 23\/Feb\/09 02:48 PM in relation to ZF-5869 that \"Leading and following parts are stripped\".  The above post alludes that virtually arbritrary numbers are recognised as dates (eg 1111 is recognised as 1.1.11 -> 01. Jan.2011).\n\nSo, isDate returns true for the string \"Yesterday, I ate 1111 hamburgers\"??\n\nisDate conveniently strips the last \"9\" from 20090199 to produce 09.Jan.2009??\n\nThat defeats the purpose of checking a date!!",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=sg",
                        "name": "sg",
                        "displayName": "Steven George",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-10-06T19:44:29.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-10-06T19:44:29.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/39642",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "{quote}1111 is recognised as 1.1.11 -> 01. Jan.2011 and therefor true{quote}\r\n\r\nAnd therefore this is a bug: 1111 is not a date, if it's recognized as such, it's wrong. (reference http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Calendar_date and http:\/\/de.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kalenderdatum ). My birthday is on AHEQ316; now it's for Zend_Date to recognize it the way I meant...",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=freak",
                        "name": "freak",
                        "displayName": "Dolf Schimmel (Freeaqingme)",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-03-29T10:31:45.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-03-29T10:31:45.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41164",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ibiryukov",
                        "name": "ibiryukov",
                        "displayName": "Ilya Biryukov",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Is there any solution planned for this? The issue is almost a year (!) old.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ibiryukov",
                        "name": "ibiryukov",
                        "displayName": "Ilya Biryukov",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-06-23T08:32:15.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-06-23T08:32:15.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/41166",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "If not this issue would already have been closed as won't fix.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-06-23T11:47:20.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-06-23T11:47:20.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/42239",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=dmuir",
                        "name": "dmuir",
                        "displayName": "David Muir",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "The problem isn't just with dates. Invalid times also pass validation.\r\n\r\nZend_Date::isDate('10.45', 'HH:mm'); \/\/true\r\nZend_Date::isDate('1:1', 'HH:mm'); \/\/true\r\nZend_Date::isDate('1045', 'HH:mm'); \/\/true\r\nZend_Date::isDate('1000000045', 'HH:mm'); \/\/true\r\n\r\nI just had a situation where a time was entered as per the first example, which then got saved to the database as 00:00:10 (MySQL interprets 10.45 as 10.45 seconds).\r\n\r\nOn further inspection, it seems to me that the problem is with Zend_Locale_Format::getDate(), and not with Zend_Date per se.\r\n\r\nShouldn't fix_date being set to false prevent this from validating?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=dmuir",
                        "name": "dmuir",
                        "displayName": "David Muir",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-09-13T01:06:16.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-09-13T01:06:16.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/42905",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=anybody",
                        "name": "anybody",
                        "displayName": "Julian Pustkuchen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I'm having the same issue and in my oppinion this is a real problem because isDate makes no sense for me though.\r\n\r\nMy Example:\r\n\r\nZend_Date::isDate('0811', 'dd.MM.YYYY'); \/\/Returns true, but false would be correct!",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=anybody",
                        "name": "anybody",
                        "displayName": "Julian Pustkuchen",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2010-11-09T01:31:18.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2010-11-09T01:31:18.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46275",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=kblomqvist",
                        "name": "kblomqvist",
                        "displayName": "Kim Blomqvist",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I'm sure that Zend_Date's validation problems will be solved in ZF2, but in the meanwhile I did a validator which solves the problems addressed here. Feel free to use it, [Kblom_Validate_Datetime|https:\/\/github.com\/kblomqvist\/kblom-zf1\/blob\/master\/library\/Kblom\/Validate\/Datetime.php]. It has a little bit different API than Zend_Date, but it should be useful in forms etc.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=kblomqvist",
                        "name": "kblomqvist",
                        "displayName": "Kim Blomqvist",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-05-01T16:05:11.000+0000",
